<!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:medium;"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Kids' effort has teacher dancing for joy</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE FONT END--><br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>By JEFF DONALDSON, Staff Writer</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
COLTON - About the only thing teacher David Doughton really has in common with Michael Jackson is the shoes.<br>
&quot;All right, hit play,' Doughton said, striking the pose, standing with his back to his class one hand on his belt, his rubber-gloved hand pointed skyward.<br>
<br>
All at once, he kicked his leg high to reveal his white socks, then spun around and grabbed his belt with his gloved hand. From beneath the trademark curl, head down, Doughton began to lip-sync: &quot;Billie Jean is not my lover.'<br>
<br>
Gloria Cerritos, 14, screamed &quot;Michael!' then put her face in her hands to hide her tears and laughter. All around him the flashes from other teachers' cameras popped off the beat.<br>
<br>
An eighth-grade English teacher at Colton Middle School, Doughton was making good on a bet with his class Friday. <br>
<br>
In January, when their grades had dropped to D's, he challenged his students to achieve the best average in the school for the third term. If they did, Doughton promised, he would lip-sync a song performed by Jackson, Justin Timberlake or Cristina Aguilera.<br>
<br>
They accepted the challenge.<br>
<br>
Doughton's class went from D's to B's, or 81.1 percent, for the term spanning February to April. It was the highest average in the school and the biggest margin of improvement in Doughton's tenure as a teacher.<br>
<br>
&quot;To tell you the truth, I'd probably do it again,' Doughton said after his performance, though when he started he said he was so nervous he could barely dance.<br>
<br>
Still, when the music started, his two weeks of practice kicked in.<br>
<br>
Doughton ran up and down the rows of students, flipping hair and moonwalking as he sang. The students clapped and cheered some of the girls hid their faces.<br>
<br>
&quot;If it gets the class motivated to perform and bring their grades up, it's worth it,' Doughton said.<br>
<br>
Gloria said she thought about Doughton's promise every day as she put in an extra effort to bring her grade up from C to A. She initially suggested Doughton sing an Aguilera song, but decided &quot;Billie Jean' would be a better show.<br>
<br>
&quot;It shows he cares,' said Christian Mendoza, 14, who three months ago was getting an F in Doughton's class. He brought his grade in reading and writing up to a C.<br>
<br>
&quot;He can keep a promise,' Christian said. &quot;It's like respect. He's showing appreciation for all that we did.'<br>
<br>
Though Doughton said the bet was a small gesture to get his students excited about learning, the students say they were so inspired by the promise that they plan to keep working to achieve.<br>
<br>
Even as he finished his song, calls of &quot;Michael!' and &quot;More!' resonated throughout Doughton's room.<br>
<br>
&quot;Will you do another song next term?' someone asked.<br>
<br>
&quot;No autographs, please,' the teacher quipped, mimicking Jackson's soft voice.<br>
